# Architecture overview

DataGenerator is one engine with many faces. The Core library does all the work, and four thin
hosts call into it. This page covers the components, the data flow of a run, and the deployment
topology.

## Components

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph Hosts
        PS[PowerShell module]
        FN[Azure Functions]
        WF[WinForms client]
        FT[Foundry agent tool]
    end

    subgraph Core["DataGen.Core"]
        ORCH[Generation Orchestrator]
        SCHED[Scheduling and Boost Engine]
        VALGEN[Value Coordinator]
    end

    CFG[DataGen.Configuration]
    AB[DataGen.Abstractions]
    FOUND[DataGen.Generation.Foundry]
    TGT[DataGen.Targets]
    OBS[DataGen.Observability]

    PS --> ORCH
    FN --> ORCH
    WF --> ORCH
    FT --> ORCH

    ORCH --> SCHED
    ORCH --> VALGEN
    ORCH --> CFG
    VALGEN --> AB
    FOUND -. implements .-> AB
    TGT -. implements .-> AB
    VALGEN --> FOUND
    ORCH --> TGT
    PS --> OBS
    FN --> OBS
    WF --> OBS
    FT --> OBS
```

| Project | Responsibility |
|---------|----------------|
| `DataGen.Abstractions` | The profile and catalog model, the interfaces, and the generated-data types. No dependencies. |
| `DataGen.Core` | Scheduling, boost math, accrual, batch cadence, the orchestrator, and the value coordinator. |
| `DataGen.Configuration` | The workbook catalog reader, the run-config loader, and the validator. |
| `DataGen.Generation.Foundry` | The `IValueProvider` backed by Azure AI Foundry. |
| `DataGen.Targets` | The `ISink` factory and the target adapters. |
| `DataGen.Observability` | Application Insights logging helpers. |

## Data flow of a run

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Host
    participant Orchestrator
    participant Scheduler as Scheduling and Boost
    participant Coordinator as Value Coordinator
    participant Foundry
    participant Sink

    Host->>Orchestrator: RunAsync(config)
    Orchestrator->>Sink: OpenAsync
    loop each tick or batch fire
        Orchestrator->>Scheduler: effective multiplier at time
        Scheduler-->>Orchestrator: owed counts
        Orchestrator->>Coordinator: BuildAsync(owed counts)
        Coordinator->>Foundry: GenerateAsync(semantic fields)
        Foundry-->>Coordinator: values
        Coordinator-->>Orchestrator: EntityBatch
        Orchestrator->>Sink: WriteAsync(batch)
    end
```

The scheduling and boost engine is pure: it has no I/O, so it is unit-tested to the exact record.
The value coordinator splits each record into engine-stamped system fields (keys, audit stamps,
state) and provider-supplied semantic fields. See
[ADR-0005](./decisions/adr-0005-foundry-value-generation.md).

## Deployment topology

```mermaid
graph LR
    WB[(data-generator.xlsx)] --> CFG[Configuration]
    RC[(run-config.json)] --> CFG
    CFG --> CORE[DataGen.Core]
    CORE --> FND[(Azure AI Foundry)]
    CORE --> SINKS[(Targets: ADLS, Event Hubs, ...)]
    CORE --> AI[(Application Insights)]
```

